    'html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Growth hormone burns fat effectively, but it also raises blood sugar, causes water retention, can promote tumor growth, and costs a fortune. Researchers in the 1990s asked a reasonable question: could you isolate just the fat-burning part of GH without the rest? AOD-9604 was the answer to that question.</p>

<h2>What AOD-9604 Actually Is</h2>

<p>AOD-9604 (Advanced Obesity Drug 9604) is a modified fragment of human growth hormone, specifically amino acids 176-191 from the C-terminal end of the GH molecule. This 16-amino-acid fragment includes a tyrosine residue added at the N-terminal, which stabilizes the molecule.</p>

<p>The fragment was identified because this specific region of GH is responsible for its lipolytic (fat-burning) effects. The other biological activities of growth hormone, including its effects on blood sugar, IGF-1 elevation, and cellular proliferation, are mediated by different regions of the molecule that AOD-9604 doesn't contain.</p>

<p>In simple terms: AOD-9604 is the fat-burning slice of growth hormone, separated from everything else GH does.</p>

<h2>How It Burns Fat</h2>

<p>AOD-9604 stimulates lipolysis (the breakdown of stored fat into free fatty acids) and inhibits lipogenesis (the conversion of food energy into new fat storage). It does this by mimicking GH's interaction with beta-3 adrenergic receptors on fat cells, triggering the same fat-mobilization cascade that full GH produces.</p>

<p>The key difference from full GH: AOD-9604 does not activate the GH receptor pathway responsible for IGF-1 production. This means it doesn't raise IGF-1 levels, doesn't affect blood sugar regulation, and doesn't promote the cellular growth signals that make full GH therapy potentially problematic for long-term use.</p>

<p>In animal studies, AOD-9604 reduced body fat in obese mice without affecting food intake or overall body weight beyond the fat loss. This suggests the fat reduction comes from metabolic changes rather than appetite suppression, a fundamentally different mechanism from GLP-1 agonists like semaglutide.</p>

<h2>Clinical Trial History</h2>

<p>AOD-9604 has an unusual clinical history. It progressed through Phase 2 clinical trials for obesity in the early 2000s, sponsored by Metabolic Pharmaceuticals in Australia. The Phase 2b trial enrolled over 300 obese adults across multiple sites.</p>

<p>Results were mixed. At the highest oral dose (1mg daily), there was a statistically significant reduction in body weight compared to placebo after 12 weeks, but the magnitude was modest: approximately 2.8 kg average loss. Lower doses didn't separate from placebo consistently.</p>

<p>The program was discontinued after Phase 2b, not for safety concerns but because the efficacy data wasn't strong enough to justify the cost of Phase 3 trials for the pharmaceutical company. AOD-9604 was safe and did produce fat loss, but the oral formulation didn't produce enough fat loss to compete in the obesity drug market.</p>

<p>This history is important context. AOD-9604 isn't dangerous; it's a compound that worked but not dramatically enough for pharmaceutical development. The injectable form used in peptide therapy delivers higher bioavailability than the oral form tested in trials, which may explain why user reports of efficacy tend to be more positive than the oral trial data.</p>

<h2>What Users Report</h2>

<p>At injectable doses of 250-300 mcg daily (substantially higher bioavailability than the 1mg oral dose in trials), users commonly report noticeable reduction in abdominal fat over 4-8 weeks, improved body composition without significant scale weight changes (fat loss with muscle preservation), and minimal side effects beyond occasional injection site irritation.</p>

<p>Expectations should be calibrated. AOD-9604 is not going to produce the 15-20% body weight loss that GLP-1 agonists deliver. It's a more moderate intervention that targets fat metabolism specifically. Users who combine it with proper nutrition and exercise report the best outcomes. It's a complement to lifestyle changes, not a replacement.</p>

<h2>Dosing Protocol</h2>

<p>The standard protocol is 250-300 mcg daily via subcutaneous injection, typically administered in the morning on an empty stomach or before bed. The fasted state may enhance the lipolytic effect since insulin (elevated after eating) inhibits fat breakdown.</p>

<p>Cycle length is typically 12 weeks. Some users run continuous protocols at lower doses (200 mcg daily), while others cycle 12 weeks on, 4 weeks off. There's no published human data establishing optimal cycle length for the injectable form.</p>

<p>AOD-9604 is sometimes stacked with other fat-loss compounds. Combining it with CJC-1295/ipamorelin adds growth hormone benefits on top of AOD-9604's targeted lipolysis. Some practitioners include it in weight management protocols alongside GLP-1 agonists, though there's no research on this combination.</p>

<h2>Safety Profile</h2>

<p>AOD-9604's safety profile is one of its strongest attributes. Because it doesn't activate the full GH receptor, it avoids the side effects associated with growth hormone therapy: no blood sugar elevation, no water retention, no increased IGF-1 (which can promote tumor growth), and no joint pain or carpal tunnel symptoms.</p>

<p>The Phase 2 clinical trials documented no significant adverse effects at any tested dose. The most common complaint was mild injection site irritation with subcutaneous administration.</p>

<p>AOD-9604 has also been approved by the Australian TGA (Therapeutic Goods Administration) as a food substance, further supporting its safety at reasonable doses.</p>

<h2>Realistic Expectations</h2>

<p>AOD-9604 is best understood as a targeted fat-metabolism enhancer, not a weight loss drug in the GLP-1 sense. It works best for people who are already exercising and eating reasonably but struggling with stubborn fat deposits, particularly abdominal fat. It won't overcome a significant caloric surplus, and it won't produce dramatic weight loss on a scale.</p>

<p>What it does well is shift body composition: less fat, preserved muscle, particularly in the midsection. For people who are close to their goals but plateauing on the last layer of stubborn fat, AOD-9604 addresses a specific metabolic bottleneck that diet and exercise alone sometimes can't fully resolve.</p>
